"""
MKT Christ Commentary — 2 Kings chapters 12–14 (fill)
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-2kings-12-14-fill.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/2kings.json
- data/translation/draft/mediating/2kings.json

Key decisions in this range:
- Ch12: Joash's temple repair = shadow of Christ as the new, imperishable temple; his assassination
  by servants = type of the rejected king killed by those he came to serve
- Ch13: v5 môšîaʿ (deliverer) treated as explicit type of Christ the Deliverer; Elisha's deathbed
  arrow scene as mediation of prophetic power; v21 (bones restoring dead) already present — skipped
- Ch13:23 treated as the theological center: divine compassion rooted in Abrahamic covenant anticipates
  the new covenant in Christ
- Ch14:6 Deuteronomic individual-accountability law contrasted with Christ's voluntary substitution
- Ch14:26-27 "no one to help" (ʾên ʿōzēr) and YHWH's refusal to blot out Israel's name =
  foundational text pointing to the ultimate gracious intervention in the Incarnation
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

KINGS2 = {
  "12": {
    "1": '<p>The accession notice places Jehoash within the Jehu dynasty of Israel, linking two kingdoms in one narrative frame. Every Judahite king is measured against David; none fully measures up until the king who is both son of David and Son of God. The forty-year reign is one of Judah\'s longer ones, yet the narrative gives more space to temple administration than military achievement — the house of YHWH is the real concern.</p>',
    "3": '<p>The regnal qualifier — "the high places were not removed; the people continued to sacrifice and burn incense at the high places" — appears with striking regularity for even reforming Judahite kings. Even Jehoash, who repairs the temple, cannot achieve complete cultic centralization. This recurrent failure reveals the limit of all human reform: the external structure can be improved, but the heart that seeks rival altars remains unchanged. Only Christ who gives a new heart (Ezek 36:26) achieves the complete purification that earthly kings never could.</p>',
    "4": '<p>Jehoash\'s temple repair plan — collecting consecrated money through the priests — reflects his genuine care for YHWH\'s dwelling. The temple as God\'s house requiring human maintenance is a shadow: the permanent dwelling of God with his people requires no such upkeep. Christ as the new temple (John 2:19–21) cannot be damaged by external force, nor does it need periodic repair from human hands.</p>',
    "5": '<p>The administrative arrangement — each priest receiving money "from his own contacts" — decentralizes the collection but leads to twenty-three years of inaction (v6). The plan\'s failure reveals the limits of institutional religion: structures exist to maintain God\'s house, but institutional inertia defeats them. The contrast with Christ\'s single atoning act, which permanently accomplishes what the temple system could not, is implied in the narrative\'s quiet critique.</p>',
    "6": '<p>Twenty-three years and no repair — a remarkable detail of institutional failure. The priests were entrusted with the house of God and did not act. The theme of unfaithful stewards runs through Scripture and reaches its sharpest expression in Jesus\'s parables of unfaithful servants (Matt 25:14–30; Luke 19:12–27). Christ himself undertook the cleansing and rebuilding of the true temple (John 2:16–19) without the twenty-three-year delay of human inertia.</p>',
    "7": '<p>Jehoash summons Jehoiada and rebukes the priests — royal authority exercised in defense of the temple\'s integrity. The pattern of a king correcting unfaithful priests anticipates the tension of the prophetic tradition and reaches its climax in Jesus\'s cleansing of the temple (Mark 11:15–17), where the messianic King exercises sovereign authority over the religious establishment that had turned his Father\'s house into something else.</p>',
    "8": '<p>The priests agree to give up accepting money in exchange for giving up responsibility for repairs — an administrative solution that shifts temple maintenance out of priestly control. The theme of divided labor between king and priest in maintaining God\'s house points forward to the one who unites both offices permanently: Christ as king who also serves as great high priest (Heb 7:17–26), making all such institutional arrangements obsolete.</p>',
    "9": '<p>The chest with a bored hole in its lid, placed beside the altar — a practical innovation to ensure transparency in temple offerings. The freewill gifts of the people flowing into the chest for the repair of God\'s house is a shadow of the community of the new covenant whose members contribute to the building up of the body of Christ (1 Cor 3:9; Eph 4:16). Both point to the desire of God\'s people to honor his dwelling.</p>',
    "10": '<p>The king\'s secretary and the high priest counting and bagging the money together — royal and priestly authority jointly overseeing temple resources. This dual oversight echoes the Zerubbabel-Joshua partnership after exile and anticipates the permanent union of kingly and priestly oversight in Christ. The careful accounting also points to the accountability that governs stewardship of what belongs to YHWH.</p>',
    "11": '<p>The counted money paid to workers — carpenters, builders, masons — who worked on the house of the LORD. The image of skilled craftsmen rebuilding God\'s house connects to Bezalel\'s tabernacle work (Exod 31) and Hiram\'s temple labor (1 Kgs 7). The new covenant community is described in similar terms: each member contributing different gifts to build up the body, which is the new temple (1 Cor 3:10–15; Eph 2:20–22).</p>',
    "12": '<p>The procurement of materials — timber and cut stone — for structural repairs to the house of the LORD. These are costly materials; the generosity of the offering sustains the building project. The theme of costly materials given for God\'s dwelling runs from the tabernacle through Solomon\'s temple; its fulfillment is Christ himself, who is both the costly gift and the permanent dwelling (John 1:14).</p>',
    "13": '<p>No silver bowls, snuffers, or trumpets were made from the repair money — it all went to structural work, not vessels. The distinction reveals a priority: the building\'s structure before its furnishings. The temple\'s vessels — instruments of worship — would be provided in due course, but the house itself must first stand. The new covenant\'s "house" (the body of believers) is similarly built up before its full glory is revealed.</p>',
    "14": '<p>The accountability system worked: the workers were trusted, the money was used for its stated purpose. The moral of the administrative detail is transparency and faithfulness in stewardship. The contrast with the earlier priestly failure (v6) is the text\'s implicit lesson: proper oversight enables faithfulness. Christ, the faithful steward who "received" all that the Father gave him and lost none (John 17:12; 18:9), is the ultimate fulfillment of trustworthy administration.</p>',
    "15": '<p>"They did not require an accounting from the men who received the money … because they dealt honestly." Trust extended because integrity was demonstrated. This snapshot of a moment when Israel\'s institutional life worked as it should — honest workers, trusted administrators — is a faint echo of the community governed by the Spirit, where the love of Christ shapes conduct without external compulsion (2 Cor 5:14).</p>',
    "16": '<p>The guilt and sin offering money was kept separate — it "belonged to the priests." The Levitical distinction between funds for temple maintenance and funds for the priestly income is preserved. The elaborate financial distinctions of the Mosaic system — maintained here in the midst of reform — anticipate the single, comprehensive atonement of Christ, who through one offering makes all such distinctions permanent history (Heb 10:12–14).</p>',
    "17": '<p>Hazael attacks Gath and threatens Jerusalem. The Aramean threat from the north, which had oppressed Israel, now turns against Judah. YHWH permits external enemies to press against his covenant people when they have not fully returned to him. The perpetual vulnerability of Jerusalem to surrounding powers under human kings contrasts with the city that "cannot be moved" whose king is YHWH himself (Ps 46:5) and with the heavenly Jerusalem that needs no defense because the Lord God is its light (Rev 21:23).</p>',
    "18": '<p>Jehoash buys off Hazael with the temple treasures — the consecrated gifts of Jehoshaphat, Jehoram, and Ahaziah, plus his own gifts, plus all the gold in the temple and royal treasury. The pattern of depleting the temple treasury to purchase military relief appears repeatedly in Judah\'s history (1 Kgs 15:18; 2 Kgs 16:8; 18:15). Sacred resources traded for temporary political safety — the inversion of covenant priorities. Christ does the reverse: he gives himself — the sacred treasure — so that his people might be permanently secure.</p>',
    "19": '<p>The regnal close formula — "the rest of the acts of Joash … are they not written in the Book of the Chronicles of the Kings of Judah?" — preserves the theological witness of the Davidic line for future readers. Every king in the line, however flawed, is recorded; the chronicle is kept because the line to Christ must not be lost. The faithfulness of YHWH in preserving the record is as much a Christological act as the content of any individual reign.</p>',
    "20": '<p>Jehoash is assassinated by his own servants at Beth-millo. The king who repaired the temple and bought off Jerusalem\'s enemies dies not in battle but by conspiracy — killed by those close to him. This pattern of the legitimate king betrayed and killed by intimate associates recurs in Israel\'s history and reaches its typological climax in Christ, delivered by one of the Twelve (Matt 26:14–16) and killed at the hands of those he came to serve (John 1:11).</p>',
    "21": '<p>The assassins are named: Jozachar son of Shimeath and Jehozabad son of Shomer. Their names are preserved; they are not anonymous. The detail serves the principle of accountability — the guilty are named. Yet burial occurs "with his ancestors in the city of David," which preserves the Davidic continuity despite violent death. YHWH\'s covenant with David is not broken by kings who die by violence; the line continues toward the one who rises from death permanently (Rom 1:4).</p>'
  },
  "13": {
    "1": '<p>The synchronistic dating — "in the twenty-third year of Joash son of Ahaziah, king of Judah" — weaves the Northern and Southern narratives together into one redemptive timeline. Both kingdoms move through their respective histories within YHWH\'s single plan. The alternating narrative structure of Kings mirrors the biblical conviction that all history — including the history of fractured, failing kingdoms — is directed toward a single goal.</p>',
    "2": '<p>"He did evil in the sight of the LORD, following the sins of Jeroboam son of Nebat" — the standard Northern evaluation. Jehu\'s dynasty begins with promise (2 Kgs 10) and immediately reverts. The "sins of Jeroboam" — the golden calves at Bethel and Dan — are not merely political compromises; they are a rival liturgy, an alternative mediation of YHWH\'s presence. Only Christ removes the rival mediations permanently by making himself the sole mediator (1 Tim 2:5).</p>',
    "3": '<p>YHWH\'s anger burns against Israel and he gives them into Hazael\'s hand. The covenant curse operates: covenant unfaithfulness produces foreign domination. The mechanism is not arbitrary but covenantal — the very nations YHWH had Israel expel now return as his instruments of discipline. This pattern finds its ultimate resolution when Christ absorbs the covenant curse for his people (Gal 3:13), breaking the cycle of sin–discipline–incomplete repentance.</p>',
    "4": '<p>Jehoahaz "sought the favor (<em>ḥillāh ʾet-pᵉnê</em>) of the LORD, and the LORD heard him, for he saw the oppression of Israel." The gracious responsiveness of YHWH to even a compromised king\'s prayer is the theological center of the verse. "The LORD heard him" — YHWH as the God who hears, in contrast to the deaf idols of the nations (Ps 135:15–17). This compassion for the oppressed anticipates the incarnate Son who "heard" and came when there was no one left to help (v26).</p>',
    "5": '<p><strong>môšîaʿ</strong> — "a deliverer" (H3467, hiphil participle of <em>yāšaʿ</em>) — YHWH gave Israel a deliverer so they escaped Aramean power. The identity of this deliverer is unnamed — possibly an Assyrian king who weakened Aram, or a later figure. The anonymity is theologically significant: the deliverer is YHWH\'s gift, not a human initiative. The term <em>môšîaʿ</em> is the same root as "Messiah" (<em>māšîaḥ</em>, anointed one) and "Jesus" (<em>Yēšûaʿ</em>); this deliverer is a type of the ultimate Deliverer who sets his people free from a power no human coalition can overcome.</p>',
    "6": '<p>"But they did not turn from the sins of the house of Jeroboam … they continued in them." Even after deliverance, no repentance follows. The pattern is painfully consistent: crisis produces prayer, prayer produces rescue, rescue produces continuation in sin. This cycle reveals the insufficiency of external deliverance without internal transformation. Christ\'s deliverance is not merely rescue from an enemy but the giving of a new heart (Jer 31:33; Ezek 36:26) that breaks the cycle permanently.</p>',
    "7": '<p>"For Hazael had left Jehoahaz no more than fifty cavalry, ten chariots, and ten thousand foot soldiers; the king of Syria had destroyed them and made them like the dust at threshing." Military diminishment as a consequence of apostasy. The tiny remnant of Israelite military force is the divine commentary on what trust in Jeroboam\'s calves produces. The people cannot defend themselves; only YHWH can save — and he does, through an unnamed deliverer (v5). The weakness of the people makes divine rescue the only available logic.</p>',
    "8": '<p>The regnal close for Jehoahaz — "are they not written in the Book of the Chronicles of the Kings of Israel?" — preserves the witness even of sinful Northern kings. The chronicle is kept, the testimony is maintained, because YHWH\'s purposes run through even corrupt lines. The habit of historical witness-keeping is itself a shadow of the faithfulness of YHWH who does not forget his people or his promises, however long the narrative of failure extends.</p>',
    "9": '<p>Jehoahaz "rested with his ancestors and was buried in Samaria; his son Joash reigned in his place." The brevity of the burial notice for a Northern king — no "city of David" for the North — marks the absence of the covenant burial ground. Samaria is not Jerusalem; the Northern dynasty lacks the covenantal geography of the South. Yet YHWH continues to work even through Northern kings, sustaining his purposes toward the one king who will be buried in Jerusalem and not remain buried (Matt 27:60; 28:6).</p>',
    "10": '<p>The accession of Jehoash (Joash) of Israel — "in the thirty-seventh year of Joash king of Judah" — another synchronistic link. The same name (Joash/Jehoash) for simultaneous kings of both kingdoms creates narrative complexity; the narrator navigates it carefully. Two kings with the same name, both failing differently: the Northern Jehoash fighting Amaziah of Judah, the Southern Joash assassinated. The fractured covenant community needs a king who unifies, not one who competes within it.</p>',
    "11": '<p>"He did evil in the sight of the LORD; he did not turn away from all the sins of Jeroboam son of Nebat." The formula repeats for each Northern king — a theological drumbeat of covenant failure. The monotony of the formula is itself the point: the structural problem of the Northern kingdom is not a fixable administrative failure but a root-level rejection of YHWH\'s mediation at Jerusalem. No internal reform can address a problem this deep; only the one who is himself both temple and sacrifice can resolve it.</p>',
    "12": '<p>The regnal summary notes Jehoash\'s military exploits — including his battle with Amaziah (ch14) — and closes. The Northern king\'s military success against Judah (ch14:11–14) is not celebrated but noted; it represents the tragic spectacle of God\'s covenant people fighting each other. The new covenant community, built on Christ\'s reconciling work, makes the warfare of the old order obsolete: "there is neither Jew nor Greek … for you are all one in Christ Jesus" (Gal 3:28).</p>',
    "13": '<p>Jehoash buried "in Samaria among the kings of Israel; his son Jeroboam sat on his throne." The dynasty continues into Jeroboam II, the most powerful of the Northern kings — who will also do evil. The persistence of the Jehu dynasty (four generations promised in 2 Kgs 10:30) is YHWH\'s faithfulness to his word even within a corrupt royal line. This fidelity to promises made even to sinful instruments reflects the same faithfulness that will sustain the Davidic line through all its failures until Christ.</p>',
    "14": '<p>Elisha\'s deathbed scene is among the most charged in the narrative. Joash king of Israel comes down to Elisha weeping: "My father! My father! The chariots of Israel and its horsemen!" — the same cry Elisha made at Elijah\'s ascent (2 Kgs 2:12). The prophet is Israel\'s true defense; the word of YHWH through the prophet is more effective than the entire military apparatus. This reaches its fulfillment in Christ, the Word made flesh, who is the ultimate defense of his people — not with chariots or cavalry, but by his death and resurrection.</p>',
    "15": '<p>Elisha instructs Joash to take bow and arrows — physical objects to enact a prophetic symbol. The prophet\'s use of concrete objects to embody divine promises runs through the prophetic tradition (Jeremiah\'s yoke, Ezekiel\'s siege-mime). The arrows become vessels of a divine promise; their proper use depends entirely on the king\'s faith and urgency. The capacity to receive the prophetic promise is the condition of its fulfillment.</p>',
    "16": '<p>Elisha places his hands on the king\'s hands as Joash draws the bow — the prophetic laying on of hands mediating divine power through human action. This is a concentrated image of prophetic intercession: the prophet\'s authority over the king\'s own, joined hands directing the shot. Christ, the prophet who is himself the word he speaks, does not merely lay hands on his people\'s actions — he inhabits them through his Spirit, enabling the action the human alone cannot perform.</p>',
    "17": '<p>"The LORD\'s arrow of victory, the arrow of victory over Aram!" The prophetic declaration over the shot transforms it from military exercise into divine promise. The word of God names what the physical act means; the oracle authorizes the action. Christ\'s own declarations — "It is finished" (John 19:30); "I am the resurrection and the life" (John 11:25) — are similarly oracular: they declare the divine reality that his physical acts enact, transforming death into victory.</p>',
    "18": '<p>Elisha commands the king to strike the ground with arrows. Joash strikes three times and stops. Three is an incomplete number here — the prophet\'s subsequent anger makes clear that five or six times would have meant complete victory. The physical act mediates the prophetic promise, and the act\'s measure determines the fulfillment\'s extent. Half-measures produce half-results. The call of the gospel is to complete, unreserved trust — giving all, not a portion, to the one whose promise is complete victory.</p>',
    "19": '<p>"You should have struck five or six times; then you would have defeated Syria completely. But now you will defeat Syria only three times." Elisha\'s anger reveals that the king\'s restraint was not modesty but insufficient trust. The story functions as a warning against treating divine promises with partial engagement. Christ\'s invitation is to full faith — "ask and you will receive, that your joy may be complete" (John 16:24) — not the cautious three-strike engagement that leaves the enemy with room to regroup.</p>',
    "20": '<p>Elisha dies and is buried. The death of the greatest Northern prophet closes an era; his bones lie in the tomb. The verse immediately pivots to Moabite raiders in the spring — the dangerous world continues without the prophet\'s presence. Yet the very next verse (v21) will show that Elisha\'s power persists beyond his death, a unique anticipatory sign of one whose power over death is not merely residual but complete and permanent.</p>',
    "22": '<p>Hazael\'s oppression of Israel throughout Jehoahaz\'s reign is now summarized retrospectively. The Aramean pressure was the divine instrument of discipline for covenant unfaithfulness. The external enemy and the internal apostasy are theologically linked: "the LORD gave them into the hand of Hazael" (v3). The discipline was real and prolonged — not a brief crisis but a reign-long pressure. Christ bears the weight of this accumulated covenant failure in his own body, absorbing it once and definitively (1 Pet 2:24).</p>',
    "23": '<p>"But the LORD was gracious to them (<em>wayyᵉḥonnēm</em>) and had compassion on them (<em>wayyᵉraḥᵃmēm</em>) and turned to them because of his covenant with Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob." The two Hebrew verbs — <em>ḥānan</em> (grace, undeserved favor) and <em>raḥam</em> (compassion, womb-love) — name the foundation of Israel\'s rescue. The basis is explicitly the Abrahamic covenant — not Israel\'s merit, not their prayer, but YHWH\'s prior commitment. "He would not destroy them, and he has not cast them from his presence — until now." This verse is the theological heart of Israel\'s survival through a century of failure; it anticipates the new covenant in Christ, who grounds grace in the same Abrahamic promise (Gal 3:16–18) and whose compassion for the lost and suffering (Matt 9:36) is this same <em>raḥam</em> given incarnate form.</p>',
    "24": '<p>Hazael dies. The great oppressor of Israel is removed — not by Israel\'s military action but by death. The instrument of divine discipline passes; the pressure is relieved by circumstances YHWH controls. The rise and fall of the powers who oppress God\'s people is consistently under his governance; the most feared enemy does not outlast his usefulness. Christ\'s ultimate victory is the final end of all the powers that have ever oppressed (1 Cor 15:24–26; Rev 20:14).</p>',
    "25": '<p>Jehoash recovers the cities from Ben-hadad that Hazael had taken from Jehoahaz — a partial restoration. "Three times Joash defeated him and recovered the cities of Israel." The three-arrow prophetic sign is fulfilled exactly (v19) — neither more nor less than was enacted in the prophetic mime. The fulfillment of the prophetic word, even in its limited form, demonstrates that YHWH\'s word does not return empty (Isa 55:11), though its scope is bounded by the faith of the recipient.</p>'
  },
  "14": {
    "1": '<p>Amaziah\'s accession in the second year of Jehoash of Israel — the synchronisms continue to weave the two kingdoms\' histories together under YHWH\'s single governance. Each Judahite king is measured by the Davidic standard; none achieves it fully. The accession notices in Kings function as a running commentary on the gap between the promised Davidic king and the actual kings who fill the throne — a gap Christ finally closes.</p>',
    "2": '<p>Amaziah is twenty-five years old at accession and reigns twenty-nine years. His mother is Jehoaddan of Jerusalem — a Judahite queen mother, which gives him an undiluted Judahite lineage. The length of his reign is significant (twenty-nine years) but will be marked by a serious failure of pride (vv8–14). The contrast between long reign and moral failure is a recurring Judahite pattern.</p>',
    "3": '<p>"He did what was right in the sight of the LORD, yet not as David his father had done." The qualifying phrase — "yet not as David" — is the key. The Davidic standard is not merely a moral bar but a covenantal one: David\'s wholehearted trust (<em>šālēm</em>) is what Amaziah lacks. "In all respects he followed the example of his father Joash" — a double qualification: like Joash, not like David. The standard recedes toward perfection that no earthly king achieves; Christ alone is the king whose heart is entirely after the Father (John 8:29).</p>',
    "4": '<p>The high places remain — again. The persistent failure to achieve complete cultic centralization marks even the best Judahite kings. The people\'s continued sacrifice at local shrines represents the divided loyalty that Deuteronomy diagnoses and prohibits. The new covenant\'s answer is not a better centralized temple but the indwelling Spirit who makes each believer a temple (1 Cor 6:19), eliminating the need for any particular physical locus of worship (John 4:21–24).</p>',
    "5": '<p>Amaziah executes the servants who assassinated his father Joash — justice for treachery. The act is presented straightforwardly as royal accountability: those who killed the king are themselves killed. The rule of law within the covenant community is a shadow of the divine justice that YHWH will ultimately execute; no crime against his anointed goes unanswered permanently.</p>',
    "6": '<p>"But the sons of the murderers he did not put to death, in keeping with what is written in the Book of the Law of Moses: \'Parents shall not be put to death for their children, nor children for their parents; each person shall die for their own sin.\'" Amaziah deliberately cites Deuteronomy 24:16 as the restraint on his vengeance. The principle of individual accountability — each person dies for their own sin — is Mosaic law at its most precise. The New Testament does not abandon this principle; it transforms it: Christ dies for others\' sins <em>voluntarily</em> and as their <em>substitute</em>, not as a violation of the Deuteronomic rule but as its transcendence through willing self-offering (Isa 53:5–6; 2 Cor 5:21).</p>',
    "7": '<p>Amaziah kills ten thousand Edomites in the Valley of Salt and captures Sela (later Petra), renaming it Joktheel. The victory over Edom recalls David\'s subjugation of Edom (2 Sam 8:14) — Amaziah is momentarily in Davidic territory militarily. But the victory inflates him dangerously; his next move is to challenge Jehoash of Israel (v8). Military success without wisdom becomes the occasion of pride and ruin. The pattern is the inverse of Christ, whose greatest victory — the cross — looks like defeat and produces no pride in the victor.</p>',
    "8": '<p>Amaziah\'s challenge to Jehoash — "Come, let us meet face to face" (<em>nitrayʾeh pānîm</em>) — is a call to battle. The verb <em>rāʾāh</em> in the hitpael carries the sense of a formal encounter that will decide status. Amaziah\'s Edomite victory has overextended his confidence. The challenge is a mistake that the narrative immediately frames as folly through Jehoash\'s parable response.</p>',
    "9": '<p>Jehoash\'s parable — "A thornbush in Lebanon sent word to the cedar of Lebanon: Give your daughter to my son in marriage. But a wild animal in Lebanon came by and trampled the thornbush." The parable is a miniature of wisdom literature: the thornbush presumes to negotiate with the cedar as an equal, and is destroyed by a casual passer-by. Amaziah is the thornbush; Jehoash is the cedar; Judah will be the trampled. The parable\'s wisdom is sharp: know your scale before issuing challenges. Christ never mistakes his scale — he empties himself, not because he overestimates others, but because his lowering is purposeful (Phil 2:6–8).</p>',
    "10": '<p>"Yes, you have struck Edom, and it has gone to your head" (<em>wᵉnāśāʾ libbᵉkā</em> — "your heart has been lifted up"). Pride after limited success is the text\'s diagnosis. "Be satisfied with your glory and stay home." The advice is pragmatic and sound; Amaziah ignores it. The lifted heart (<em>rûm lēḇāḇ</em>) is a recurring warning in Deuteronomy (17:20) against kings who forget who gave them victory. Christ\'s heart is not lifted by success; he "did not count equality with God a thing to be grasped" (Phil 2:6) even at his highest.</p>',
    "11": '<p>Amaziah refuses to listen. The narrative moves quickly from Jehoash\'s wise warning to battle, locating the confrontation at Beth-shemesh in Judah — already on Judean territory, which means Amaziah has either invaded Israel or Israel has pushed deep into Judah\'s heartland. The battle is on home soil, making the defeat that follows maximally humiliating.</p>',
    "12": '<p>"Judah was routed by Israel, and every man fled to his home." The complete rout — the covenant community self-destructing in internal warfare. "Every man fled to his home" is a phrase of total military collapse (see also 1 Kgs 22:36); the army dissolves rather than retreats in order. The tragic spectacle of Israel fighting Judah, of YHWH\'s people at war with YHWH\'s people, is the nadir of covenant failure. Christ is the peace between the divided peoples — and in the eschatological vision, the twelve tribes are united again under the one shepherd (Ezek 37:22; John 10:16).</p>',
    "13": '<p>Jehoash captures Amaziah at Beth-shemesh and brings him to Jerusalem — then breaks down 400 cubits of Jerusalem\'s wall from the Ephraim Gate to the Corner Gate. The Davidic king captured, the holy city\'s defenses breached: this is a humiliation at the level of sovereignty. The wall that protects Jerusalem — the place YHWH chose for his name — is torn down by the Northern king. The city is exposed; the king is a prisoner. Only the New Jerusalem, whose walls are the glory of God (Rev 21:23–25), will never be breached.</p>',
    "14": '<p>Jehoash takes all the gold and silver from the temple and palace, the hostages, and returns to Samaria. The pattern of temple treasury depletion recurs — Shishak (1 Kgs 14:26), Jehoash himself (2 Kgs 12:18), now Jehoash of Israel. The repeated despoiling of the temple mirrors the repeated failure of the covenant people. Christ\'s body, the new temple (John 2:21), cannot be permanently despoiled — the resurrection restores what crucifixion stripped away.</p>',
    "15": '<p>The regnal summary of Jehoash — "how he fought against Amaziah king of Judah" is one of the listed achievements — reflects the Northern narrator\'s perspective that this was a military victory. The irony is that the "winner" of this Israelite-Judahite battle contributed to the mutual weakening of both kingdoms before Assyria. Internal victories that leave everyone weaker are not victories at all; the prophetic tradition consistently identifies the true enemy as apostasy, not the neighboring covenant kingdom.</p>',
    "16": '<p>Jehoash buried in Samaria with the kings of Israel; Jeroboam II reigns in his place. The transition to Jeroboam II sets up the most prosperous (and spiritually stagnant) era of the Northern kingdom. Power and prosperity without covenant faithfulness is not blessing but deeper entanglement — a theme Amos will address directly to this generation. Jeroboam\'s prosperity is a gift of YHWH\'s compassion (v26–27), not a reward for obedience.</p>',
    "17": '<p>Amaziah survives Jehoash by fifteen years — a detail that complicates any simple theology of "obedience brings success, sin brings defeat." Amaziah was defeated, humiliated, had Jerusalem\'s wall torn down — yet he lives and reigns another decade and a half. The relationship between covenant faithfulness and earthly outcome is not mechanically predictable. Providence works through the complex pattern of history; its ultimate logic is disclosed only in Christ, whose suffering and death lead to resurrection glory (Luke 24:26).</p>',
    "18": '<p>The close formula — "the rest of the acts of Amaziah — are they not written in the Book of the Chronicles of the Kings of Judah?" — preserves the witness even of a king whose reign was marked by pride and defeat. The chronicle\'s fidelity to the record — including failures — is the narrative counterpart of the theological honesty that runs through Kings: the Davidic line produced many kings who fell short, and the text does not hide it, because the final David\'s glory does not depend on the interim kings\' success.</p>',
    "19": '<p>Conspiracy in Jerusalem; Amaziah flees to Lachish; his pursuers kill him there. The same pattern as Joash his father (2 Kgs 12:20): Judahite kings assassinated by servants/conspirators. Two generations of Judahite kings murdered from within — the covenant community devouring its own leadership. The vulnerability of earthly Davidic kings to betrayal from within is the shadow side of the messianic expectation: only the king who cannot be ultimately destroyed will secure his people permanently.</p>',
    "20": '<p>"They brought his body back on horseback, and he was buried in Jerusalem with his ancestors in the city of David." Even after assassination in Lachish, Amaziah is returned to Jerusalem for burial in the city of David. The covenant geography of the Davidic burial place is maintained even for defeated, murdered kings. The body is honored in death; the Davidic continuity is maintained in the burial ground. Christ is buried in a tomb and raised from it; his burial is real, his resurrection permanent — the fulfillment of the Davidic promise that "you will not abandon my soul to Sheol" (Ps 16:10; Acts 2:27).</p>',
    "21": '<p>The people of Judah make Azariah (Uzziah) king at sixteen — a smooth succession despite the assassination of his father. The covenant community maintains the Davidic line even through crisis. Azariah will have a long and largely positive reign (2 Kgs 15:1–7; 2 Chr 26); the dynasty\'s persistence despite repeated violence against its kings is itself a sign of YHWH\'s faithfulness to the covenant with David. No assassination can sever the line that will produce Christ.</p>',
    "22": '<p>Azariah "built up Elath and restored it to Judah" — a small territorial recovery at the southern tip of Judah on the Red Sea. The detail is noted as a positive achievement at the beginning of a long reign. The pattern of progressive territorial restoration and loss in Judah mirrors the trajectory of the covenant: periods of recovery followed by contraction, all within YHWH\'s governing purpose. The full territorial restoration awaits the messianic era (Ezek 47:13–23).</p>',
    "23": '<p>Jeroboam II\'s accession — "in the fifteenth year of Amaziah son of Joash, king of Judah" — places Israel\'s most powerful king within the synchronized history. Jeroboam II reigned forty-one years (the longest Northern dynasty reign), restoring the territory of Israel to its Solomonic extent. His power is remarkable; his theology is condemned in v24. The coexistence of maximum territorial reach and continued apostasy makes him the emblem of external success without covenant faithfulness.</p>',
    "24": '<p>"He did evil in the sight of the LORD; he did not turn away from all the sins of Jeroboam son of Nebat." The formula is unchanged despite the unprecedented prosperity of his reign. Power, territory, and prosperity do not alter the theological assessment — YHWH judges by covenant faithfulness, not by any other metric. This is the prophetic tradition\'s fundamental claim, which Amos and Hosea (both active in Jeroboam II\'s era) will develop at length: wealth is not blessing if the covenant is broken.</p>',
    "26": '<p>"For the LORD saw how bitterly Israel was suffering; there was no one left, slave or free, and no one to help Israel" (<em>wᵉʾên ʿōzēr lᵉyiśrāʾēl</em>). The divine compassion is awakened by the total helplessness of the people — not by their merit but by their extremity. "No one to help" is the language of abandonment (also Lam 1:7; Ps 22:11) — the people utterly without a defender. YHWH\'s intervention in this situation is the pattern for the Incarnation: God enters the situation where no one else can help (Rom 5:6: "while we were still helpless, Christ died for the ungodly").</p>',
    "27": '<p>"But the LORD had not said he would blot out the name of Israel from under heaven." This is the theological ground of Jeroboam II\'s deliverance of Israel: not merit, not prayer, but YHWH\'s prior refusal to abandon his covenant name-promise. "So he delivered them by the hand of Jeroboam son of Joash" — a sinful, apostate king as the instrument of divine rescue. YHWH\'s faithfulness to his promise is not blocked by the unworthiness of his instruments. Christ himself enters through a genealogy that includes both saints and sinners (Matt 1:1–17) because YHWH\'s faithfulness runs through, not around, human failure.</p>',
    "28": '<p>Jeroboam II "recovered Damascus and Hamath for Israel" — the Davidic-Solomonic territory at its northernmost extent. The prophet Jonah son of Amittai had prophesied this restoration (v25, though not listed in this verse). The fulfillment of prophetic words even through sinful instruments demonstrates that YHWH\'s word is not contingent on the holiness of its mediators. The word achieves its purpose (Isa 55:11) regardless of the instrument\'s character — a principle that reaches its fullest expression in the prophetic word becoming flesh in Christ.</p>',
    "29": '<p>Jeroboam rested with his ancestors; his son Zachariah reigned in his place. The closing of Jeroboam II\'s long reign is brief. The dynasty ends quickly after him — Zachariah is assassinated after six months (2 Kgs 15:10), the last of the Jehu dynasty. The four-generation promise (2 Kgs 10:30) is fulfilled exactly. YHWH\'s word holds even when the beneficiary of the promise is corrupt; his faithfulness to his word is not a reward for the dynasty\'s merit but a demonstration of his own character.</p>'
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-christ', '2kings')
    merge_comm(existing, KINGS2)
    save_comm('mkt-christ', '2kings', existing)
    for ch in ['12', '13', '14']:
        print(f'  ch{ch}: {len(existing.get(ch, {}))} verses')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
